snippet.textDisplay:
If you are in a high loot area please don't kill alarms or arc. They will help you notice other players more easily and if you talk to them while hidden they are more hesitant to make a move. 

They might set up an ambush tho as you are trying to leave so think of creative ways of getting in and out of buildings. Sometimes it's better to take fall damage than walking into a trap.

snippet.textDisplay:
If everything is quiet and then some guy just happens to show up pretending to be friendly right when you extract, he's probably been following you just to kill you when you press the extract button. The first time this happenes to you, it will inevitably be right after you successfully farmed all the pain in the ass items you need to upgrade one of your benches.

If you're that guy, I hope you outlive all of your friends and family, including your children.

statistically, if more than 50% of the players you meet are friendly, (which is definitely the case in solos), that means the person u meet is more than likely not
interested in killing you.  at greater than 50% friendly, from a game theory perspective minimizing unnecessary firefights is less about determining whether someone else is trustworthy and more about ensuring the other player knows you are.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually finally had a "good" PvP moment. Was in the new map, checking some of the ruptured shipping containers shelves, and a guy shot me from across the gap. Not expected, especially with all the flying enemies in there.

But I had multiple things he didn't expect. The tactical aug that drops a smokebomb; a medium shield; a clear idea of where to take cover; adequate healing supplies to get back to full... and a shotgun when he platformed over to see if I'd dropped any loot.

Cheeky bugger was on a free loadout. No wonder I survived.

Use deadline mines on the queens legs. Guaranteed 1000 damage and watch pieces fall off to loot. Use a snap hook on the queen and plant them on her head. Use the hook to get away fast.

Use trigger nades 3 at a time then pull the trigger when you want. Guaranteed to put down any full health raider.

When going inside. Shoot rocketeers and wasps so they come and guard the door behind you so you cant be followed.

snippet.textDisplay:
There are a few problems with this guide: 

1. You are not considering console controls for tweaking settings; PC is not the default experience.

2. You assume almost every encounter with players will be hostile, and not doing a solo run; perhaps you can make suggestions for a more chill run?

3. For Quick-use items, I recommend heals, shield charger, smoke grenades (can buy them), and Adrenaline shots (as you said); It's all you need for a solo experience. 

If you're feeling generous, safe-pocket some defibs to help a brotha out.

snippet.textDisplay: This tip may sound basic but I bet a lot of new players don't think about this,  set up your gear in the same way all the time.  This way you don't have to look at the screen to pick what you want.   Mine is always shield, heal, adrenaline, smoke, grenade.  Plus I'll put any consumables I want to swap like extra grenades or zip line on the right side of my inventory.   No hunting around,  I know exactly where they are.

snippet.textDisplay: Dude emoted don't shoot.  Then was getting killed by wasps.  I did him a favor and hullcracked down all his aggro.  We was in a small area behind town hall by the hatch.  So he healed up. Kept circling around and being weird.  Not responding.  So I was onto him then. I gave him one last chance and emoted don't shoot. He didn't respond. He actually goes to set a mine at the hatch as I'm watching him. Then it was decision time.  I had to put him down with the venator. And of course he was a free loadie with nothing good. But I felt I saved the lobby from a sneaky rat.
